n- node CPU spike\n- node memory consumption\n- node disk read I/O consumption \n- node disk write I/O consumption \n- node disk space consumption\n\nAnomaly Cluster Description:\nHere is the RCA analysis result in plain English:\n\n```\n{\n  "Cluster 1": {\n    "Key Findings": "Node-5.productcatalogservice-2 experienced network packet drops, while node-2 reported high system network bytes sent. Shippingservice-2 had log anomalies related to timeouts.",\n    "Root Cause": "Possible network congestion or misconfiguration affecting product catalog service and shipping service."\n  },\n  "Cluster 2": {\n    "Key Findings": "Node-5.productcatalogservice-2 continued experiencing network packet drops, while frontend-1.source.frontend.jaeger-collector reported high request durations. Shippingservice-2 had a log anomaly related to timeouts.",\n    "Root Cause": "Possible sustained network congestion or misconfiguration affecting product catalog service and shipping service."\n  },\n  "Cluster 3": {\n    "Key Findings": "Frontend-1.source.frontend.jaeger-collector reported high request durations, while shippingservice-2 had a log anomaly related to timeouts.",\n    "Root Cause": "Possible performance issue or misconfiguration affecting frontend service and shipping service."\n  },\n  "Cluster 4": {\n    "Key Findings": "Node-5.productcatalogservice-2 experienced network packet drops, while frontend-1.source.frontend.jaeger-collector reported high request durations. Shippingservice-2 had log anomalies related to timeouts, and a trace anomaly in the CartService.",\n    "Root Cause": "Possible sustained network congestion or misconfiguration affecting product catalog service, frontend service, and shipping service."\n  }\n}\n```\n\nNote that I\'ve applied the RCA decision rules provided to determine the root cause for each cluster.\n\nRelevant Historical Incidents (if any):\n[Past Incident 1] (Score: 0.541)\nComponent: shippingservice-1 | Metrics: HTTP, gRPC, heap, network, packet loss, rr, rt, socket\nSummary: Component: shippingservice-1\nEvent: shippingservice-1 failure at 2022-03-20 16:10:03\nSystem Type: Banking Microservice (pod)\nSymptoms: container network packet retransmission; The ground truth explicitly identifies the failure as \'container network packet retransmission\' in \'shippingservice-1\' at 2022-03-20 16:10:03.; Anomalies in the Istio proxy sidecar for \'shippingservice-1\' were detected (\'istio_agent_go_memstats_heap_released_bytes\' at 16:12:00), suggesting the proxy was under stress, which is consistent with ; Upstream services began reporting errors at the time of the incident. For example, \'cartservice-2\' reported \'istio_request_bytes.http.500.\' anomalies starting at 16:10:00.\nAffected Metrics: HTTP, gRPC, heap, network, packet loss, rr, rt, socket\nRoot Cause Category: The root cause of the incident was container network packet retransmission within the \'shippingservice-1\' pod, as stated in the ground truth. This net\nFailure Pattern: The root cause of the incident was container network packet retransmission within the \'shippingservice-1\' pod, as stated in the ground truth. This network-level issue caused the pod to become unresponsive or slow, leading to cascading failures for upstream services that depend on it. The anomaly reports do not show the specific retransmission metric but capture the resulting symptoms, such as HTTP 500 errors and gRPC UNKNOWN statuses in dependent services starting at the time of the incident.\nMitigation Principles: Enhance monitoring to include container-level network metrics such as TCP retransmission rates (e.g., from `netstat` or eBPF) to enable direct detection of this failure type. Review resource allocation for the shippingservice pods and their sidecars, as resource pressure can degrade network performance. Implement more robust circuit-breaking and retry policies in upstream services to mitigate the impact of downstream network issues.\n\nBackgroud:\n"\n\n\nBased 